“​​A year after Uvalde, officers who botched response face FEW CONSEQUENCES—A [Washington] Post investigation finds numerous higher-ranking officers who made critical decisions remain on the job” I have no experience with courts in Uvalde county, so I can't say anything ab judge incompetence or corruption there.
   I do know that Minneapolis courts are a particular abomination of one hand washing the other in a cesspool of corruption. This is among many other similar court systems of varying degrees.  But I have first-hand experience in Minnesota (and Maryland) courts, and I’m quite sure they are in the bottom layer of the cesspool.
   A very important point here (that I will keep repeating) is that after the 1983 Feldman MISTAKE by the Sup Ct, the federal courts erroneously got a "quasi-magical means of docket-clearing" (a good phrase the 6th circuit federal appeals court picked up from the Tulsa Law Review).  Feldman allowed stupid and/or lazy federal judges (probably the majority) to let their state-court pals do WhateverTF they want, which solidified the court system into one massive fraud impenetrable to the Bill of Rights.  With the current exception of the 1st circuit (Boston) there's really only one, integrated court system.  It allows all judges federal and state to stick together as an unaccountable bulwark against the Constitution.  Maybe the 4th circuit in Richmond, VA is fully figuring-out the Feldman Goof, but it’s not yet completely clear, which illustrates (and I’ll be showing it to you) the impossibility of making clear law using words alone.  Booleans are required.  And clear law is actual law because ambiguous law is phony “law.”  People who are genuinely free can see the “bright line” dividing the right side of the govt’s law from the wrong side.  If it’s a smudgy line from the judge-fudge sludge—such as the effluent from the Minnesota Superfund sites called “law schools”—then it’s not law.  It’s a dictatorship that’s no better than any other rathole dictatorship in defining phony “law.”
   I will get a public debate on this eventually, so my advice to the press is to expose this now, so you’re not later shown to be asleep at the switch while I give you the root cause of Mr. Floyd’s death, as well as every major US domestic problem.  (And no, I’m not exaggerating.)  They will ignore me, of course, until they can’t.  Back to the Uvalde nightmare…..
   I do know that judges everywhere are unaccountable and face zero consequences for their incompetence or corruption.
   I do know that the media, by and large, are fellow travelers with the lawyer-monopoly-mob: they are bamboozled by the AccordinglyMoreverIndeed jargonistic patter of lawyer wordpushing.  I call this the Dear Alphonse—little kids using excessively-formal talk to try to sound like adults.  They are the umbrellasteppers from the playground—intoxicated with the power of words to command people to do whatever silly thing they want.  BTW, AccordinglyMoreverIndeed is deliberately smushed together because so many lawyers/judges just string together their jargon in a smush to create an intimidating impression, which works very well on most people—until you dig into it (which the media don't do) and find it's garbage.

I have some post-trauma stress & survivor's guilt (affecting me some days more than others) from my plane crash and aftermath, which I deal with but cannot escape.  Writing this stuff helps me.  Nor should I be allowed to escape it.  It’s the gift-curse combo of a second life.  I'm particularly reminded of it every day by physical pain and disability, but I remind myself that it’s nothing compared to what countless others over eons have experienced—so many of whom never got a second chance, given that I should be a ghost...and sort of am.
   Of course the hardest thing is contemplating the purely innocent—kids less than a tenth my age—who never had a chance to play red rover or four-square or the stupid umbrellastepping, pre-law game.  I've always told my daughter about things I remember when I was her age (and I remember a great many things).  I want her to know that I remember what the world looks like from a kid's view.  This adds to my pain about the Ulvade kids and other kids—among them, those in Ukraine bc I stayed in Irpin and spent some time in Bucha at a park and some restaurants; and also in downtown Kiev and in Poltava.  A second life doesn't come for free.

And in case I didn't mention it here—but I'll say it again anyway—corrupt, unaccountable judges telegraph the Anything Goes signal to bad cops whose antennae are up and ready to receive it.  Good cops know better.  So I don't know about Uvalde courts and their role, if any, in the massacre, but I do know that no police bullet was in an innocent Uvalde victim, in contrast with what has happened plenty of times in Minneapolis.

So now…about the Minneapolis press.  As I've written many times, when I read the 2/10/20 corrupt-drivel from Kevin the Hennepin-Menace Burke—the Minneapolis simpleton-fraud-judge—I knew instantly that Minneapolis was a "small circle of friends."  I used this Phil Ochs phrase to a MPLS federal court a few months later at the time of Mr. Floyd.  I also immediately knew, on 2/10/20, that the Star Tribune was a member of the MPLS judge-lawyer-politician gang.
   I knew because Burke had been there 35 years, and it was a good bet that he had written some similar bilge during that time.  And it was a good bet that someone had told the Star Tribune about Burke.  A real newspaper would have exposed Burke and the MPLS gang.  On the other hand there are no real newspapers in the US, bc none will take on the court system...though the LA Times' Aug 2022 exposé on the CalBar corruption giving the big-shot lawyer the free pass for years is a step in the right direction.

A Feb 2023 LA Times  article quotes: “The State Bar is committed to continued reform of our regulatory and disciplinary duties to address these serious issues.”  Disbarring the bar will end the concentration of power and attendant corruption. This solution was identified ~150 years ago.  Lord Acton was inducted into the Rock & Roll History Hall of Fame (along with Three Dog Night for Eli Whitney’s Coming) on a very cold January 1976 night in Sweet Lorain County, Ohio.

So a few months ago I saw positive confirmation of the pseudo-newspaper Star Tribune's failure to identify 35 years of the simpleton-fraud judge Burke.

https://https://twitter.com/JudgeKSB/status/1641259999342080000…

Rochelle Olson, who is "Politics and Government reporter" for the Star Tribune is pals with Burke.  Any way it's cut, Ms. Olson is not a competent reporter.  Though it's possible she gets see-no-evil marching orders from Star Tribune editors, a real reporter is supposed to obtain facts (I know this from Perry White).  A real reporter—particularly one covering local government—would not under any circumstances be pals with a judge who had been a court kingpin for 35 years where the entire US has been aware for some time that there are skittish trigger-happy cops who point-blank innocents or dubious "suspects" with toddlers in a car seat mere feet away.
   Qualified immunity-schmunity: courts enforce the law on law enforcement.  If courts are rotten, bad cops with antennae up for the Anything Goes signal will receive it loud and clear.
   After I read Burke's bilge (no relation to Burt's Bees), I made a quick search on Burke.  I found the 7-yr-old's horrific death by pit bull:
   "Since August 2006, Minneapolis Animal Control has contacted Judge Kevin Burke 15 times about two Australian Shepherds owned by the judge. Most of the calls were for barking, but Burke did receive two warning letters when his dogs bit another dog on a walk and a mail carrier had to use chemical irritant to stop one of the dogs from charging at him. Seven of the reports were marked as unfounded."
   "Burke said..It never occurred to me that any calls about my dogs would be an issue." [Really?]
   "Burke said his previous dealings with Animal Control had no impact on his ruling in the case against Zachary King Sr."
THAT'S NOT THE LEGAL STANDARD for judge disqualification—not in Minnesota, not federally, probably not anywhere.  When I read that in Feb 2020, that was the first confirmation of my hypothesis that the Star Tribune was playing ball with know-nothing Burke & the rest of the MPLS gang.
